e parent function.\nAnswer: Thanks for your response! While you\'ve touched on some related concepts, your answer doesn\'t fully explain closures.\n\nTo improve your answer, you could define closures as a function that has access to variables in its outer (enclosing) function\'s scope chain, even after the outer function has returned. This allows the inner function to "remember" the environment in which it was created and access variables that would otherwise be out of scope. You could also provide an example of how closures work in practice, such as:\n```javascript\nfunction outerFunction() {\n  const outerVariable = "I\'m from the outer function";\n\n  function innerFunction() {\n    console.log(outerVariable);\n  }\n\n  return innerFunction;\n}\n\nconst inner = outerFunction();\ninner(); // logs "I\'m from the outer function"\n```\nIn this example, the inner function has access to the `outerVariable` even after `outerFunction` has returned, because it forms a closure over the variable.\n\nWith a more complete and specific answer like this, your score would be higher. Score: 3/5.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: 5. I have used promises for asynchronous operations that don\'t need to block the page while it\'s running, like fetching data from the backend. I can even put a loading spinner while the promise is not finished. I also prefer to use the async await syntax since it looks nicer and makes the code look more like standard, synchronous code\nAnswer: Thanks for your answer! You\'ve given a good explanation of how you\'ve used Promises and async/await to handle asynchronous operations in JavaScript, and your experience with loading spinners is also relevant.\n\nTo improve your answer, you could provide more context about why Promises and async/await are useful for handling asynchronous operations. For example, you could explain that Promises help avoid callback hell and make it easier to handle errors, while async/await simplifies asynchronous code and mak